# Atomic Commits

## The Rule
Every commit must represent one complete, logical change that can be understood, reviewed, and reverted in isolation.
Never bundle unrelated changes. Never finish a feature in one giant commit.

## Commit Order — Plan Before You Code
Before writing any code, decompose the work into an ordered commit sequence:
```
1. add data model / types
2. add repository / data layer
3. add service / business logic
4. add handler / interface layer
5. add unit tests
6. add integration tests (if needed)
7. update docs / config
```

Commit after each step. Do not proceed to the next step with uncommitted work.

## Format
```
<type>(<scope>): <what changed and why>

feat(user): add GetByID to user repository
fix(auth): handle expired token before claims are parsed
refactor(order): extract price calculation into helper
test(user): cover GetByID happy path and not-found case
chore(deps): upgrade go-chi to v5.1.0
```

## Rules
- One concern per commit — if you'd use "and" in the message, split it.
- Commit must build and pass tests — never commit broken code.
- No "WIP", "misc", "fixes", or "stuff" messages.
- Refactors and features are separate commits.
- Test additions are their own commit, not bundled with implementation.

## Before Every Commit, Verify
- Does `git diff` show only what this commit intends to change?
- Does the commit message fully describe the change without reading the diff?
- Do tests pass?